ith community leaders, children, activists, gang members, and everyday people, artists developed a way of using art to help empower and represent themselves. Showcasing the depth and sophistication of the visual arts in Chicago at this time, Zorach demonstrates the crucial role of aesthetics and artistic practice in the mobilization of Black radical politics during the Black Power era.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Sep 2020) 0aAfrican American artszIllinoiszChicagoxHistoryy20th century. 0aArtists and communityzIllinoiszChicagoxHistoryy20th century. 0aBlack Arts movementzIllinoiszChicago. 0aCity planningxSocial aspectszIllinoiszChicagoxHistoryy20th century. 7aART / American / African-American.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2019z978311069632540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478002468zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478002468423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781478002468.jpg  a978-3-11-069632-5  DUK eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles